#: ../../../reference/code-blocks.md:1
msgid "Code Blocks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/code-blocks.md:3
msgid ""
"Code blocks and examples are an essential part of technical project "
"documentation. Sphinx provides syntax highlighting for these out-of-the-box, "
"through Pygments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/code-blocks.md:8
msgid ""
"Code blocks in reStructuredText can be created in various ways::\n"
"\n"
"    Indenting content by 4 spaces, after a line ends with \"::\".\n"
"    This will have default syntax highlighting (highlighting a few words and "
"\"strings\").\n"
"\n"
".. code::\n"
"\n"
"    You can also use the code directive, or an alias: code-block, "
"sourcecode.\n"
"    This will have default syntax highlighting (highlighting a few words and "
"\"strings\").\n"
"\n"
".. code:: python\n"
"\n"
"    print(\"And with the directive syntax, you can have syntax highlighting."
"\")\n"
"\n"
".. code:: none\n"
"\n"
"    print(\"Or disable all syntax highlighting.\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"There's a lot more forms of \"blocks\" in reStructuredText that can be used, "
"as\n"
"seen in https://docutils.sourceforge.io/docs/ref/rst/restructuredtext."
"html#literal-blocks."
msgstr ""

